user.biography: Home of the tallest peak in North America, Denali was the first national park established to conserve wildlife in 1917.

node.accessibility_caption: Canada Lynx sits in patch of grass. It is gray and brown with tufted ears.

node.text:
Happy #InternationalCatDay!

Canada Lynx (lynx canadenis) is Denali’s only feline resident. This elusive creature is known for its snowshoe like paws and fluffy black ear tufts. In the winter months, they have a thick coat and utilize their large paws to easily traverse across snowy plains. Like most stealthy predators, Lynx have extremely well adapted hearing and eyesight; they can often spot small prey from up to 250 ft away!

Fun Fact: The Lynx is a crepuscular species, meaning they are most active during dawn and dusk, making it an extra special wildlife spotting during the day time!

Images 1 and 2: NPS Photo/Ken Conger

node.text:
Meet Denali’s alpine wildlife! Dall sheep (Ovis dalli) are found in the high mountains of Northwestern North America, and are related to bighorn sheep. They are one of the “big five” mammals to look for in Denali; watch for them resting and feeding on ridges and steep slopes or out on the rocks and crags trying to avoid predators!

Fun Fact: Male Dall sheep are called “rams” and have large, curling, horns. Female Dall sheep are called “ewes” and have shorter, spiky, horns. The male’s horns will begin to curve around age 3, so young rams can be difficult to tell apart from ewes. 

The Denali Alpine Wildlife project (@denalialpinewildlife), with Denali National Park and Preserve (@denalinps) and the University of Montana (@umwildlife), seeks to understand how Alaska’s changing temperatures, weather patterns, and landcover are impacting where alpine wildlife can live now, and where they might be able to live in the future. 

Are you planning to visit Denali National Park, AK? Become a citizen scientist!  You can join the project by taking photographs of alpine wildlife, particularly collared pika, hoary marmots, arctic ground squirrels, and Dall sheep, while you are out hiking in the park and uploading them to iNaturalist (see the last slide for instructions) or emailing them to us at denalialpinewildlife@gmail.com.

NPS Photo / Jen Wall

Alt Text: A male Dall sheep with large, curving horns and white-colored fur is climbing a rocky mountain-side with its rear end facing toward the camera but its head turned back toward the camera as well.

node.text:
Equisetum or Horsetail, which you can find throughout Denali today, is a “living fossil”. It is the only remaining modern genus of the entire class Equisetopsida, which has dominated forest understories for over 400 million years.  Some Equisetids were large trees reaching to 100 feet tall.  Fossil stems and rhizomes of Equisetites have been found near Sable Mountain, Double Mountain, and Polychrome Mountain in Denali.  Amazingly, some stems are found relatively uncompressed and are preserved in three-dimensions.  This is because the stems are hollow and filled with sediment during burial. 

NPS Photos

#Findyourpark #livingfossils

node.text:
Tiny Wonders
Did you know there are orchids in Alaska? You may think our fierce winters and brief summers wouldn’t allow for such delicate flowers, but Alaska boasts over 30 species of orchid! 
These little beauties, called Fairy Slipper Orchids (Calypso bulbosa), were spotted along the Triple Lakes Trail in early June. The plant is 4-6 inches tall, with one flower about an inch wide per stem. After a short blooming period, the entire plant seems to disappear, and both leaf and flower die. One single new leaf grows in August, which will overwinter to await the return of the sun in the spring. 
Photo Credit: Candace Cahill

node.text:
Wild berry season is in full swing here at Denali National Park, and the bears are taking full advantage while it lasts! Many species of berries can be found in the park, including blueberries, cloudberries, red currants, arctic raspberries, and the soapberries pictured here. While soapberries, as the name implies, might not be considered the tastiest by humans, they are abundant throughout the park and provide an important food source for bears as they ready themselves for the long winter ahead. 

Keep an eye out for soapberries and bears that might be feasting on them in rocky areas along rivers and creeks. As always, be respectful of wildlife and give them their space – it’s recommended that you keep about 300 meters between you and grizzly bear to keep you both safe and happy!

Have you foraged for any wild berries this year? What kind of wild berry is your favorite?

Alt Text: Series of photos where blonde bear with dark brown paws forages for red berries from shrubby bushes. Area surrounding shrubs is a rocky creek bed. In second two images, bear is looking up and showing its face.

Photos: Baylee Bessingpas

node.text:
Did you know that wolves raise their pups as a family? A wolf pack is a family, usually made up of the mom and dad (the alpha female and male), aunts, uncles, and kids from past years. All work together to help raise the pups, teaching them how to hunt, cross rivers, and survive. Most of all, they teach the pups how to play! 

How did your community help to raise you? 

Find out more about our wolves here: www.nps.gov/dena/learn/nature/wolves.htm

Photo © Anastasia Brease

node.text:
Have you ever considered being a Junior Ranger? Participating in our Junior Ranger Program is a fantastic way for young (and young at heart) visitors to learn about wildlife, wilderness, stewardship, Indigenous peoples of the area, and much more. 

If you visit Denali, ask a ranger at any visitor center for our new and improved Junior Ranger Activity Book. If you can’t make it to our park, fear not! You can still learn about Denali and become a Junior Ranger from home by completing our Virtual Visit Activity on our park website: https://www.nps.gov/dena/learn/kidsyouth/beajuniorranger.htm.

Once you complete the necessary activities and show it to a ranger, you will receive a super cool and official Junior Ranger Badge (made of reclaimed hardwood, wow!). Best part – it’s free!

(If you are a teacher, parent, or student wanting to learn more about Denali, visit the Educational Resources page of our park website: https://www.nps.gov/dena/learn/education/education-resources.htm)

#JuniorRanger #FindYourPark #Denali #Alaska #NationalParkService #OptOutside #OutdoorEducation #EveryKidOutdoors 

NPS Photo / Emily Wong

node.text:
Slow your roll... it’s what visiting national parks is all about! 

Speeding increases your chances of high-impact collisions that kill animals – a frequent occurrence along highways everywhere and especially in parks. Slowing down in Denali can help prevent the loss of Canada Jays such as this one, as well as other furry and feathered critters who call this place their home. While driving the Denali Park Road, please note that the speed limit is never more than 35 mph and is at times slower. 

NPS Photos

node.text:
Meet Denali’s alpine wildlife! Arctic ground squirrel (Urocitellus paryii) are the largest North American ground squirrel and are fairly common throughout Denali National Park. They in be found in tundra meadows at high elevations.

Fun Fact: During hibernation, the Arctic ground squirrel’s body temperature will drop to temperatures below freezing – the coldest body temperature recorded in any mammal!

The Denali Alpine Wildlife project (@denalialpinewildlife), with Denali National Park and Preserve (@denalinps) and the University of Montana (@umwildlife), seeks to understand how Alaska’s changing temperatures, weather patterns, and landcover are impacting where alpine wildlife can live now, and where they might be able to live in the future.

node.text:
Happy #WorldRangerDay!

Today we celebrate the people who work to keep Denali National Park running. The maintenance staff, road and trail crews, firefighters, law enforcement officers, planners, administrators, scientists, HR staff, and IT technicians.

Hundreds of people work behind the scenes to keep this park running smoothly. So the next time you hike a trail, use a restroom, read a park brochure, or drive on the Denali Park Road, give thanks to the hardworking folks who make all those things happen.

Image 1 and 2: NPS Photo/Kent Miller
Image 3: NPS Photo

node.text:
In the days leading up to #WorldRangerDay, we wanted to highlight the variety of folks who work hard for Denali National Park and Preserve.

Wildlife Biologists and Technicians are responsible for studying and monitoring the animals found within Denali. Their schedules are unpredictable and varied. An average day could mean responding to wildlife in a campground, establishing and evaluating closures, educating visitors on wildlife safety, and even responding to reports of injured animals. The work they do helps keep Denali's diverse wildlife, as well as our visitors, safe. 

What Denali wildlife are you most excited about seeing?

node.text:
Did you know that you can sign up for a ranger-led hike while visiting Denali National Park? 

With titles to pique every interest, like “Fire & Ice: Forces of Change,” “Across Time and Taiga” and “Nature is Our Grocery Store,” our interpretive rangers inspire dedication while safeguarding Denali’s wilderness and promoting conservation. 

Take some time to learn about Denali’s plants and animals, geography, and climate, all while immersing yourself in the beauty and grandeur of one of Alaska’s national parks. To check availability and sign up, stop by the Denali Visitor Center on the day of your visit. 

NPS Photo / Mary Lewandowski
